Regional Availability Summary • The low-sales regional cluster is running critically short on budget skincare (5 days cover, frequent stock-outs) and is marginal on premium skincare (9 days cover).
• Other regions are holding 18–26 days of budget skincare, 11–26 days of premium skincare, and more than 30 days of budget makeup – clear evidence of inventory sitting where demand is already satisfied.
• Q1 sell-out in the cluster (budget skincare: 130 u, premium skincare: 300 u) is far below the forecast implied by the days-cover figures, indicating demand is being suppressed by lack of stock, not by lack of shoppers.
• Budget makeup is the only item the cluster has in relative excess (20 days cover against falling demand).
• North and East have emerging premium skincare risk (5 days and 4 days cover respectively), but East has 300 u arriving in 7 days – no immediate shortage once the in-transit shipment lands.

Key Problems

Systemic under-allocation of budget skincare to the low-sales cluster. 40 units on hand cover only 5 days of a forecast that must be close to 8 units/day. This is driving the “declining” trend – shoppers simply do not find the item.
Inventory mis-positioning: West alone is sitting on 520 units of budget skincare (26 days). Across West, South and East there are ~1,360 excess units that could be redeployed.
Data silo between Sales and Inventory teams delays re-supply decisions, causing allocations to follow historical sales instead of forward demand.
Excess budget makeup everywhere (30–34 days cover) ties up working capital while contributing little to revenue because demand is soft or falling.
Looming premium skincare tightness in North and East requires a small but prompt top-up to avoid replicating the budget-skincare problem there.
Business Impact • Lost revenue: the cluster is probably missing 400–500 units of budget skincare sales per quarter (>€40-50 k) and a halo of premium cross-sell.
• Market share erosion: budget skincare is the entry door to the brand; out-of-stock drives consumers to competitors and undermines promotional spend.
• Working-capital drag: idle makeup stock (~2,000 u company-wide) locks up cash and warehouse space.
• Service-level variance: strong regions operate at ≥98 % availability while the cluster is below 85 %, damaging brand consistency.

Recommended Next Actions Immediate (next 7 days) • Execute an emergency lateral transfer of 180 units of budget skincare from West (120 u) and South (60 u) to the low-sales cluster. This lifts the cluster to ~23 days cover and drops donor regions to still-safe 18–20 days, restoring shelf presence without new production.

Medium-term (next 30 days) • Stand-up a weekly cross-functional “Available-to-Serve” call (Sales, Supply Planning, Regional Logistics) using one shared cloud worksheet that shows forecast, on-hand, and in-transit for every SKU/region. Target: keep all core SKUs between 14–24 days cover; trigger re-balancing or production when out of band.

Highest-priority recovery action • Re-balance and lock minimum 14 days safety stock of budget skincare in the low-sales cluster via transfers and, if needed, a 500-unit fast make-to-stock lot in week 2. Reason: budget skincare is the gateway product – without it, the region cannot grow any other category.

Issue requiring coordination between Sales and Inventory teams • Real-time re-forecasting logic: Sales must feed weekly promotion and outlet expansion plans into the inventory file so that Supply can shift or build stock before demand hits, avoiding both stock-outs in weak regions and excess in strong ones.
